**Most critical gap**: The AES session key rotation rejection in `dispatch/checkin.rs` (`red-cell-c2-tz9m`). This is the only defence against replay attacks where an attacker captures a CHECKIN frame and uses it to push a known key into an active session. The guard exists and appears correct, but has zero test coverage — any accidental deletion or condition inversion would be completely invisible.

**Overall test quality**: The batch is split between well-tested and completely untested code. `audit.rs`, `auth.rs`, and `demon.rs` have thorough coverage with good test names and meaningful assertions. The entire `dispatch/` submodule (assembly, checkin, filesystem, kerberos, network) has **zero inline tests** — all five files contain only production code with no `#[cfg(test)]` blocks. `database.rs` has 3 tests covering only two private helpers. `dispatch/mod.rs` has some tests but the dispatch sub-handlers have none.
